Orchestrates three expansion passes (count resolution, type-append, line-flag annotation) that transform a parsed dictionary into `TypedEntry` records ready for rendering. The core entry point is `expand_dict()`, which filters out `@type` entries (used to build the append pool), runs count expansion on each remaining entry, appends types, fixes family terminals, and annotates one-liners.

`ExpandedEntry` is the Pass A output: counts resolved, no `repeat`/`dcount`/computed chunks remain. `TypedEntry` is the final output: every `%t` slot filled, `terminal` and `one_liner` flags set, ready to render. Both preserve the original `Entry` for diagnostics.

`expand_dict(entries, generic_arg_strokes)` returns `Vec<TypedEntry>` or `ExpandError`. It builds the type set from `@type` entries; if `generic_arg_strokes` is `None`, the append pool is the full arity-0 set, otherwise filtered to only the named strokes. `@type` entries are consumed (filtered out before expansion), not emitted. Each non-type entry is count-expanded (via `expand_counts`), then each count variant is type-expanded (via `expand_types_one`), then the batch is post-processed by `fix_family_terminals` and `expand_line_flag`.

The modules are task-specific: `counts` handles `repeat`/`dcount`, `append` fills `%t` slots, `lineflag` sets one-liner flags, `types` builds the append pool, `family` marks non-terminals, `infinite` contains rendering logic and type construction. Never panics on user input.